05114nam a22006855i 9780271030395DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710303957 a10.1515/97802710303952doi  a(DE-B1597)584386  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHC110.P6bW43 2006eb 7aSOC0260202bisacsh04a362.5/56809732221 aPickering, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWelfare Reform in Persistent Rural Poverty :bDreams, Disenchantments, and Diversity /cKathleen Pickering, Mark H. Harvey, Gene F. Summers, David Mushinski. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRural Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Rural Places, State Welfare Policies, and Theoretical Bases -- tPart I What the Numbers Tell Us -- t2 Welfare Caseloads: Changes in Public Assistance Program Use -- t3 Labor Markets: From Tanf to Low-Wage Part-Time Jobs -- t4 Poverty: Family and Community Well-Being -- tPart II What the People Told Us -- t5 Welfare Reform on the Reservation, South Dakota -- t6 Welfare Reform in Appalachia, Kentucky -- t7 Welfare Reform in the Rio Grande Valley, Texas -- t8 Welfare Reform in the Mississippi Delta, Mississippi -- t9 Welfare Reform in Persistent Rural Poverty -- tAppendix A: Tanf Participant Respondent Characteristics -- tAppendix B: Cluster Counties and Reservations -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act of 1996 was enacted, policy makers, agency administrators, community activists, and academics from a broad range of disciplines have debated and researched the implications of welfare reform in the United States. Most of the attention, however, has focused on urban rather than rural America. Welfare Reform in Persistent Rural Poverty examines welfare participants who live in chronically poor rural areas of the United States where there are few job opportunities and poor systems of education, transportation, and child care. Kathleen Pickering and her colleagues look at welfare reform as it has been experienced in four rural and impoverished regions of the United States: American Indian reservations in South Dakota, the Rio Grande region, Appalachian Kentucky, and the Mississippi Delta. Throughout these areas the rhetoric of reform created expectations of new opportunities to find decent work and receive education and training. In fact, these expectations have largely gone unfulfilled as welfare reform has failed to penetrate poor areas where low-income families remain isolated from the economic and social mainstream of American society. Welfare Reform in Persistent Rural Poverty sheds welcome light on the opportunities and challenges that welfare reform has imposed on low-income families situated in disadvantaged areas. Combining both qualitative and quantitative research, it will be an excellent guide for scholars and practitioners alike seeking to address the problem of poverty in rural America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aRural poorzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh1 aHarvey, Mark H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSummers, Gene F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271030395zCo-access DOI >